        content: 'An encumbrance is any claim, lien, charge, or liability attached to real property that may diminish its value or affect its use but does not necessarily prevent transfer of title. Surveyors encounter encumbrances regularly during title research and must understand how they affect property rights.\n\nRestrictive Covenants (Deed Restrictions): Private agreements that limit how property can be used. They are created when a developer or grantor includes restrictions in the deed or records them as part of a subdivision plat. Common restrictions include minimum building setbacks, architectural style requirements, prohibition of commercial use in residential areas, and minimum lot sizes. Restrictive covenants run with the land and bind all subsequent owners. They are enforced by other property owners within the same subdivision or development who benefit from the restrictions. Covenants can become unenforceable if neighborhood conditions change so dramatically that enforcement would be inequitable (the doctrine of changed conditions) or if the covenant violates public policy or fair housing laws.\n\nLiens: A lien is a legal claim against property as security for a debt. The property cannot be sold free and clear until the lien is satisfied (paid). Types of liens include:\n\nMortgage Liens: Created when a property owner borrows money using the property as collateral. The mortgage is recorded in the public records and creates a lien that remains until the loan is paid off.\n\nMechanic\'s Liens (Construction Liens): Filed by contractors, subcontractors, or material suppliers who have not been paid for work performed on the property. The lien attaches to the property even though the lienholder has no ownership interest.\n\nTax Liens: Imposed by the government for unpaid property taxes, income taxes, or other tax obligations. Tax liens generally take priority over all other liens.\n\nJudgment Liens: Result from court judgments against a property owner. If a property owner loses a lawsuit and a monetary judgment is entered, the judgment can be recorded as a lien against the owner\'s real property.\n\nMortgages: While a mortgage creates a lien (discussed above), it also represents a specific legal arrangement between borrower and lender. In "lien theory" states, the borrower retains title and the lender holds a lien. In "title theory" states, the lender holds legal title until the loan is paid. Most states follow lien theory. Surveyors need to recognize mortgages in the chain of title because they represent encumbrances that must be satisfied or assumed in any property transfer.',
