        content: 'Surveyors must be skilled at locating, interpreting, and weighing various forms of evidence found in public records. The quality and relevance of evidence varies, and understanding the hierarchy of evidence is fundamental to professional surveying practice.\n\nTypes of Records and Where to Find Them:\n\nCounty Recorder\'s Office (Register of Deeds): Deeds, mortgages, easements, liens, subdivision plats, condominium declarations, and other instruments affecting real property. This is the primary source for title research.\n\nCounty Assessor\'s Office: Tax maps, assessment records, property descriptions used for taxation, and ownership information. Tax maps are useful for preliminary research but are not authoritative legal documents.\n\nCounty Surveyor\'s Office: Filed surveys, corner records, section corner ties, and survey monuments. Many states require surveyors to file their surveys with the county surveyor.\n\nCourt Records: Boundary dispute decisions, quiet title actions, partition suits, and condemnation proceedings. Court decisions interpreting property boundaries can be binding on subsequent surveys.\n\nState and Federal Records: GLO (General Land Office) plats and field notes for PLSS states, state land office records, BLM records, and federal patent documents.\n\nWeighting Evidence: Not all evidence carries equal weight. The surveyor must evaluate evidence based on several factors:\n\nOriginal Survey Evidence: Field notes, plats, and monuments from the original survey carry the greatest weight because they reflect the intent at the time of the original conveyance.\n\nMonumental Evidence: Physical monuments found in the field (iron pins, stone monuments, marked trees) are generally preferred over record evidence (written descriptions) because they represent what was actually done on the ground.\n\nTestimonial Evidence: Statements from landowners, neighbors, and elderly residents about long-standing boundaries, fence locations, and traditional property use can be valuable, especially when physical and record evidence is ambiguous.\n\nReputation Evidence: General community knowledge about boundary locations, sometimes referred to as "common reputation," can support boundary determinations, particularly for boundaries that have been recognized for generations.',
