        content: 'Property ownership in the United States is often described as a "bundle of rights" or "bundle of sticks." Each right in the bundle can be separated and conveyed independently. Understanding these rights is essential for surveyors who must interpret deeds and determine what was actually conveyed.\n\nSurface Rights: The right to use and occupy the surface of the land. This includes the right to build structures, cultivate crops, and make improvements.\n\nMineral Rights (Subsurface Rights): The right to extract minerals, oil, gas, coal, metals, and other subsurface resources. Mineral rights can be severed from surface rights, meaning one person can own the surface while another owns the minerals beneath it. This is common in oil-producing and mining regions. When mineral rights have been severed, the mineral owner typically has an implied right of surface access to extract the minerals, which can significantly affect the surface owner\'s use of the property.\n\nAir Rights: The right to use the space above the surface. These rights have become increasingly important in urban areas where buildings, bridges, and other structures may extend over property boundaries or easements.\n\nWater Rights: The right to use water on, under, or adjacent to the property. Water rights are governed by different doctrines depending on the state (riparian rights in eastern states, prior appropriation in western states, as covered in the Water Boundaries reading).\n\nTimber Rights: The right to harvest standing timber. These can be conveyed separately from the surface estate.\n\nDevelopment Rights: The right to develop or improve the property. These can be limited by zoning, restrictive covenants, or conservation easements.\n\nSurveyors must carefully read deeds to determine which rights are being conveyed. Phrases like "excepting and reserving all mineral rights" or "together with all appurtenant water rights" indicate that specific rights are being excluded from or included in the conveyance.',
