        title: 'Unwritten Rights: Acquiescence and Practical Location',
        content: 'Beyond adverse possession (covered in the Boundary Law Principles reading), several other doctrines can establish or modify boundaries without a written instrument. Surveyors must understand these because they can override the record boundary.\n\nBoundary by Acquiescence: When adjoining landowners treat a visible line (usually a fence, hedge, or wall) as their common boundary for a long period, the law may recognize that line as the legal boundary regardless of where the record boundary is actually located. The requirements vary by state but generally include: (1) a visible line of demarcation (fence, wall, hedge), (2) acquiescence by both parties for the statutory period (often the same as the adverse possession period), and (3) uncertainty or dispute about the true boundary location. Some states require that the acquiescence be "mutual" (both parties knowingly accept the line), while others only require passive acceptance.\n\nBoundary by Agreement (Practical Location): When adjoining landowners genuinely dispute their common boundary and resolve the dispute by agreeing on a specific line, that agreed-upon line becomes the legal boundary. Requirements typically include: (1) a bona fide dispute or uncertainty about the boundary, (2) an agreement (oral or written) to a specific line, and (3) subsequent occupation or use consistent with the agreement. The agreement must be based on a genuine dispute; owners cannot arbitrarily relocate a known boundary by agreement.\n\nBoundary by Estoppel: When one landowner makes representations about the boundary location (such as pointing out a line to the neighbor), the neighbor relies on those representations and makes improvements (such as building a structure near the represented line), and the first landowner later tries to claim the boundary is elsewhere, the first landowner may be estopped (prevented) from asserting the true boundary.\n\nParol Agreement: An oral (unwritten) agreement about a boundary. Under the Statute of Frauds, agreements concerning real property generally must be in writing. However, courts recognize exceptions for boundary agreements that have been acted upon, particularly when the parties have occupied in accordance with the agreement for a significant period.',
