        title: 'State and Local Law',
        content: 'Most law directly affecting property boundaries and surveying practice comes from state and local sources.\n\nState Statutes: State legislatures enact laws governing real property, surveying licensure, and related topics. Important categories include:\n\nProperty Law: Recording acts (determining priority between competing claims), statutes of limitations (including adverse possession periods), statutes of frauds (requiring certain agreements to be in writing), and homestead exemptions.\n\nSurveying Practice Acts: Every state has a practice act that defines surveying, establishes licensure requirements, and sets standards of practice. These acts typically require professional licensure to perform boundary surveys, define the scope of surveying practice versus engineering and other professions, and establish continuing education requirements.\n\nRecording Statutes: Three types exist across the states:\n- Race Statutes: The first person to record their deed wins, regardless of notice.\n- Notice Statutes: An unrecorded deed is void against a subsequent purchaser who takes without notice and for valuable consideration.\n- Race-Notice Statutes: The subsequent purchaser must both take without notice AND record first to prevail.\n\nMinimum Standards for Surveys: Many states have adopted minimum technical standards for surveys, specifying accuracy requirements, monument types, plat contents, and certification language.\n\nLocal Ordinances: County and municipal governments adopt zoning ordinances, subdivision regulations, building codes, and other local laws that affect surveying. Local regulations often specify required setbacks, lot dimensions, access requirements, and plat approval procedures.\n\nAdministrative Regulations: State boards of licensure adopt administrative rules that implement the practice act. These rules may include specific standards of conduct, continuing education requirements, and disciplinary procedures.',
