        title: 'Legal Descriptions: PLSS vs. Metes and Bounds vs. Lot and Block',
        content: 'Three primary systems are used to describe property in the United States. Surveyors must be proficient in all three.\n\nPLSS (Government Rectangular Survey) Descriptions: Used in 30 states, primarily west of the Appalachians. Properties are described by reference to the rectangular survey framework: township, range, section, and quarter-quarter sections. Example: "The SW 1/4 of the NE 1/4 of Section 15, Township 3 North, Range 5 West, Principal Meridian." This describes a 40-acre parcel. PLSS descriptions are read from right to left on the ground — start with the section, find the NE 1/4, then find the SW 1/4 of that quarter.\n\nMetes and Bounds Descriptions: Used in the original thirteen colonies and their derivative states, and within the PLSS for irregular parcels. These describe the boundary by a sequential series of courses (directions) and distances starting from a Point of Beginning (POB), as detailed in the Common Law Principles reading.\n\nLot and Block (Recorded Plat) Descriptions: Used in subdivisions and developments where a surveyor has prepared a plat (map) that is recorded in the public records. Properties are described by reference to the recorded plat: "Lot 15, Block 3, Sunset Hills Subdivision, as recorded in Plat Book 45, Page 123, County Records." The plat itself contains the detailed metes and bounds or coordinate descriptions of each lot. Lot and block descriptions are the simplest to interpret because the survey has already been performed and recorded.\n\nWhen describing property for the FS exam, you should be comfortable reading and interpreting all three types of descriptions and understanding how they interact (for example, a metes and bounds description within a PLSS section, or a lot and block reference to a subdivision within a PLSS quarter-quarter).',
